    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "1ba9cc34faed8927",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "1ba9cc34faed8927",
        "text": "From the perspective of the 1990s and the present, however, one must regret this omission. With [[Bruno Latour]]'s and especially [[Harrison C. White]]'s network theories, sociology has developed a body of theory that can compete with that of systems theory. Networks are structures that have exactly the same value of describing uncertain expectations that Luhmann formulated for his concept of structure. One could have considerably improved both the empirical scope and, relatedly, the analytical acuity of systems theory if one had early on incorporated a network concept that, entirely in the sense of Maturana, allowed one to describe the structures, as concrete as they are exchangeable, in which the autopoiesis of the basal operations of social systems, which empirically always remains somewhat abstract, takes place."
